          "body": "Joseph's temptation is not a single dramatic crisis but a sustained campaign. The narrator identifies four escalating stages: the initial proposition (39:7), the daily pressure (39:10), the manufactured opportunity (39:11), and the physical assault (39:12). This fourfold pattern is pastorally significant: most serious temptation does not arrive as a single, obvious assault that any person of ordinary moral sense would recognize. It arrives as sustained, incremental, increasingly intimate pressure that erodes resistance over time. Joseph's response is equally graduated: articulate, theologically grounded refusal for the daily assault (39:9-10); physical, uncompromising flight for the moment of physical contact (39:12). Both modes of resistance are necessary; neither alone would have been sufficient. The NT draws exactly this pattern: Paul commands the Corinthians to 'flee immorality' (1 Corinthians 6:18) — the same *nus* Joseph employs — because immorality is the one sin where verbal negotiation eventually fails."
