          "title": "Joseph's theological ethics: sin against God, not merely against man (39:9)",
          "body": "The moral center of the chapter is Joseph's extended refusal speech in 39:8-9, and its center is the final clause: 'How then could I do this great evil and sin against God?' Calvin, commenting on this verse, observes that Joseph names the offense against his master (39:8) but identifies it as secondary — the primary reason for refusal is vertical, not horizontal. This is the chapter's most counter-cultural claim. In both the ancient Egyptian world and the modern secular one, ethics are primarily social: what harms others, what breaks agreements, what violates social contracts. Joseph frames his ethics theologically: what violates the character and commands of the God who is present with me. This is also Psalm 51:4 in narrative form — David's later confession, 'Against You, You only, I have sinned,' is the same theological instinct Joseph demonstrates here. Jonathan Edwards wrote that all sin is ultimately an infinite offense because it is directed against an infinite God; Joseph's formulation anticipates that logic centuries before it is systematized."
