          "body": "The beged (garment) of Joseph threads through five verses (39:12, 13, 15, 16, 18) and functions as the chapter's most charged symbol. Joseph flees, leaving the garment behind — it is the physical token of his moral act: he will not keep everything in his hands if keeping it means keeping sin. But the abandoned garment is immediately weaponized. Potiphar's wife seizes it not merely as evidence but as a prop for an already-constructed narrative. She holds it until Potiphar returns (39:16) — premeditated, not impulsive. The garment that Joseph left to preserve his integrity becomes the instrument used to condemn him for the very sin he refused to commit. This is the chapter's most bitter irony. The same motif has already appeared in the Joseph narrative: in chapter 37, the brothers used Joseph's coat to deceive Jacob. In Genesis, garments consistently mark moments where truth is inverted. The garment that should testify 'I fled' is made to testify 'he assaulted.' But the narrator's commentary is unmistakable: the garment in her hand does not change what YHWH knows, or what YHWH does in the verses that follow."
