          "body": "Joseph's imprisonment is unjust by every human standard — he is punished for the act he refused to commit. Peter Davids and other NT scholars observing the Joseph narrative as a typological template for suffering-and-exaltation note that Genesis consistently uses false accusation as the mechanism of divine advancement: the lowest point in Joseph's external circumstances is the precise location of his next divine appointment. The king's prison (*bet sohar*) is where Pharaoh's own disgraced servants are confined — and it is exactly there that Joseph will meet the cupbearer and baker (chapter 40), whose dreams will lead to Pharaoh's dreams, which will lead to Joseph's throne. What Potiphar intends as punishment, YHWH uses as positioning. The narrator signals this by repeating the prosperity formula in the prison verbatim: 'whatever he did, the LORD made to prosper' (39:23) echoes 39:3. The prison is not a detour from the plan; it is the plan. This is the chapter's gospel shape: the one who suffers unjustly for righteousness is not outside God's purposes — he is at the center of them."
