        "number": 2,
        "title": "Sustained temptation met by articulate, theologically-grounded refusal",
        "range": "39:7-10",
        "excerpt": "But he refused and said to his master's wife, '…How then could I do this great evil and sin against God?'",
        "body": "The chapter's crisis begins with a look. The narrator's verb is nasa ayin — literally 'she lifted up her eyes at Joseph.' The same idiom describes Abraham looking up and seeing the three visitors at Mamre (18:2) and Joseph himself looking up and seeing his brothers approaching (37:25). Here it is the predatory gaze of desire. The invitation is stark and unadorned: 'Lie with me' (39:7). The Hebrew has no decoration — no seduction, no pretense, just a direct command in two words. This is not romance; it is acquisition.\n\nJoseph's refusal in verses 8-9 is the most theologically important speech in the chapter. He constructs a two-tiered argument. The first tier is horizontal and social: my master has trusted me with everything, withholding only you — to take you would be to betray the trust that has been placed in me (39:8). This is an appeal to honor, to covenant fidelity within a household. But Joseph does not stop there. The second tier is vertical and theological: 'How then could I do this great evil and sin against God?' (39:9). The Hebrew word for sin is chata — to miss the mark, to fall short of the standard. The standard here is not social convention or household code but the character of the God who is with him. Calvin observed that Joseph's identification of the primary offense as against God, not against Potiphar, demonstrates that he was governed not by fear of man but by fear of God — a distinction that is the foundation of all genuine moral courage.\n\nThe escalation from single refusal to daily sustained resistance (39:10) is crucial for the chapter's pastoral meaning. Joseph does not resolve the problem once and thereby eliminate it. He faces it 'day after day' — and 'he did not listen to her to lie beside her or to be with her.' The second phrase is notable: he refuses even to be with her in neutral proximity. He understands that sustained proximity to sustained temptation erodes the will regardless of initial resolve. This anticipates the NT principle of fleeing rather than managing temptation (1 Corinthians 6:18; 2 Timothy 2:22).\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Maen* — he refused; a strong volitional word, not 'he hesitated' or 'he declined.' *Chata* — sin; the standard Hebrew word for moral transgression, missing the divinely set mark. *Ra gadol* — 'great evil'; the same construction used for the wickedness that preceded the flood (6:5). Joseph's language is calibrated: this is not a small impropriety but a catastrophic moral failure. *Yom yom* — 'day after day'; a Hebrew idiom for unbroken continuity of action."
