        "body": "The crisis reaches its physical climax when words can no longer hold the line. The empty house (39:11) is the manufactured opportunity — every other servant has been removed, leaving Joseph isolated. Potiphar's wife seizes Joseph's garment (taphas beged — to grab, to grasp physically) and issues the same two-word command: 'Lie with me.' Joseph's response is now not speech but action: he leaves the garment in her hand and flees. The Hebrew verb nus (to flee) is the chapter's most important human action word — bodily, urgent, unambiguous departure. There is no negotiation, no lingering to argue the case, no attempt to retrieve the garment. The garment costs what it costs; the sin would cost more.\n\nThe garment (beged) immediately becomes a weapon. Potiphar's wife constructs a false narrative in two stages: first to the household servants (39:14-15), then to her husband (39:17-18). The two accounts are nearly identical, but with a notable difference in the first: she says 'he has brought in a Hebrew to us to make sport of us' (39:14), invoking ethnic resentment — 'this Hebrew' is an outsider, an alien, a threat to the household. She addresses the servants as fellow-sufferers ('to us'), positioning herself and them as joint victims of foreign intrusion. The accusation is a masterpiece of false testimony: she takes the one undeniable fact (the garment) and inverts the narrative around it. The garment that Joseph left as the token of his flight becomes, in her retelling, the evidence of his assault.\n\nWhen Potiphar hears, 'his anger burned' (39:19). The narrator does not editorialize about whether Potiphar believes his wife; the text simply records the consequence. What is theologically significant is what does NOT happen: Joseph is not executed. Under Egyptian law and household code, a slave who assaulted the master's wife could expect immediate death. Potiphar is the captain of Pharaoh's bodyguard — he has both the authority and the means to execute Joseph on the spot. That he instead imprisons him in the royal prison has led many commentators — including Wenham in the Word Biblical Commentary — to suggest that Potiphar's 'burning anger' may not be entirely believed. The punishment is disproportionately mild for the alleged offense. Providence operates through Potiphar's restrained sentence: the prison is precisely where YHWH needs Joseph to be.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Taphas* — to grab, seize, take hold of; used elsewhere for military capture (Judges 1:6) and arresting a prophet (Jeremiah 26:8). The word carries weight — this is not a gentle touch. *Nus* — to flee, escape; the same root used of Lot fleeing Sodom (19:17, 30). *Tsachaq* — to mock, make sport; the same root used of Ishmael 'mocking' Isaac in 21:9. *Ivri* — Hebrew; an ethnic-social designation often used by foreigners to describe Israelites with a sense of otherness (cf. 40:15; 41:12; Exodus 1:15, 16)."
